## Verification

Different surfaces verify differently. Cascade reports verification results in the build log entry for the brief.

### Mechanical verification (Cascade self-reports pass/fail)

| Surface | What "verified" means |
|---|---|
| TypeScript | `tsc --noEmit` passes. No `any` types unless inline-justified with `// reason: ...` |
| Build | `next build` completes without warnings or errors |
| Linting | ESLint and Prettier pass on changed files |
| Accessibility | All interactive elements keyboard-focusable; visible focus indicators present; color contrast ≥ 4.5:1 for body text and ≥ 3:1 for large text per WCAG 2.1 AA |
| Responsive | Layout renders without overflow at 380px, 720px, 1024px, 1440px widths (Cascade checks via dev tools / playwright; Jake confirms in real Chrome) |
| Color tokens | No raw hex values in component code — only Tailwind tokens or CSS variables sourced from canon |
| Forbidden vocabulary | Grep for the forbidden words from `decisions_log.md` in any shipped copy. Zero matches required. |
| Tabular numerals | Any financial number uses `font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums` (or Tailwind `tabular-nums`) |

### Perceptual verification (Operator owns; Cascade does not self-grade)

- Whether the hook lands
- Whether type rhythm feels right
- Whether motion timing reads as ceremonial vs. busy
- Whether a section feels signature vs. generic
- Whether copy voice matches `positioning.md`

For these, Cascade implements the brief exactly, runs mechanical verification, and reports completion. Cascade does NOT assert "this looks great" or "this feels right." Those are Jake's calls in real Chrome. If Cascade has uncertainty about a perceptual decision, surface the uncertainty in the build log entry — don't paper over it.

