## What Cascade is reliable for

- Next.js route handlers, server actions, and page components from explicit specs
- TypeScript types from explicit data shapes
- Tailwind class application against a clear design spec
- Component implementations with explicit prop types
- Mechanical refactors with specific scope
- Resend integration for transactional email from a clear spec
- Form server actions with explicit validation rules
- Accessibility patterns (focus management, semantic HTML, ARIA) from a clear spec
- Responsive breakpoint implementation from canon-specified breakpoints
- Mechanical security defaults per the baseline above
- Copy insertion when the copy is final and verbatim in the brief

## What Cascade is unreliable for

- Open-ended design decisions
- Copywriting from scratch
- Brand voice calls (the positioning doc and design canon are the only sources of truth)
- Layout choices that require taste
- Anything where intent has to be interpreted
- Deciding whether motion timing "feels right" — implement the spec, let Jake verify
- Deciding whether a section is "done" perceptually — that's Jake's call
- Inventing copy for a section the brief left blank
- Interpreting whether a forbidden word's synonym is acceptable — if uncertain, ask

If a decision needs to be made — visual, copy, or architectural — the chat makes it before writing the brief. Don't ask Cascade to interpret.

